<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Incomplete on Ted Brandston</title><link>https://tedbrandston.github.io/tags/incomplete/</link><description>Recent content in Incomplete on Ted Brandston</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><atom:link href="https://tedbrandston.github.io/tags/incomplete/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>What Is Eco Friendly</title><link>https://tedbrandston.github.io/writing/what-is-eco-friendly/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://tedbrandston.github.io/writing/what-is-eco-friendly/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Writing about &lt;a href="https://tedbrandston.github.io/writing/solar-biochar-at-home.md"&gt;a solar biochar kiln&lt;/a&gt; left me thinking a lot about how to define &amp;ldquo;eco friendly&amp;rdquo;. I&amp;rsquo;ve also been thinking about it in relation to some news a friend pointed me at: &amp;ldquo;&lt;a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2016/09/to-tote-or-note-to-tote/498557/"&gt;canvas&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/24/style/cotton-totes-climate-crisis.html"&gt;bags&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="https://qz.com/1585027/when-it-comes-to-climate-change-cotton-totes-might-be-worse-than-plastic/"&gt;are&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="https://www.euronews.com/green/2020/01/22/is-your-reusable-tote-worse-for-the-environment-than-a-plastic-bag"&gt;worse&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/climate-change/sustainable-living/cotton-tote-bags-sustainable-shopping-b1909035.html"&gt;than&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="https://www.rateitgreen.com/green-building-community/discussions/plastic-vs-reusable-bags-which-bag-is-best/1340"&gt;plastic&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/579437/cotton-canvas-tote-bad-for-environment"&gt;bags&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rdquo;. &lt;a href="https://youtu.be/hFgtIziShmc"&gt;Poor Tim Minchin&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(I should note: I didn&amp;rsquo;t read all of those articles in full, most of them I skimmed. I know, I know, I know &amp;ndash; I&amp;rsquo;m part of the problem. They also mostly cite the same couple of studies. I might try to write more about that later&amp;hellip;)&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>